    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_308975135" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/308975135" />
    <a title="James" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8667453-james"><img alt="James" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/308975135?book_show_action=true">Apr 08, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="James" class="user" itemprop="url" name="James" href="/user/show/8667453-james">James</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="audio CD 9780061867200" href="/book/show/6369002-jesus-interrupted">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer308975135&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer308975135" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8580530618613445245">Ye of faith beware! In this case, the enemy - facts and history - might undermine your faith.<br/><br/>Not being a believer, I don&apos;t know how a devout Christian would react to this book. But I imagine it would be extremely difficult to keep one&apos;s beliefs intact in the face of this onslaught of historical evidence - evidence that shows the bible to be deeply flawed. It must be nigh on impossible to continue to believe the bible is the inerrant word of god.<br/><br/>Ehrman focuses on the new testament as his area of </span>
  <span id="freeText8580530618613445245" style="display:none">Ye of faith beware! In this case, the enemy - facts and history - might undermine your faith.<br /><br />Not being a believer, I don't know how a devout Christian would react to this book. But I imagine it would be extremely difficult to keep one's beliefs intact in the face of this onslaught of historical evidence - evidence that shows the bible to be deeply flawed. It must be nigh on impossible to continue to believe the bible is the inerrant word of god.<br /><br />Ehrman focuses on the new testament as his area of expertise, but of course, as it is linked by reference to the old testament, the entire bible is discussed. According to Ehrman, the new testament was most likely written by men decades after Jesus died, in a language he didn't speak and in a country where he had not lived. None of those original writings survive. And without a doubt, they have been changed over the centuries. As more ancient copies of these texts have been uncovered, there are stark differences with our current bible. <br /><br />Interestingly, there is no historical record of Jesus contemporaneous with his time on earth. The first historian to mention Jesus was the Roman historian Tacitus in the second century. However, some scholars believe the passage referring to Jesus was inserted at a later date as it incorrectly describes Pontius Pilot's position, which scholars believe Tacitus would have known.<br /><br />The number of errors and contradictions in the new testament are staggering in their breadth. One of the most interesting of these is the passage in the new testament which revolves around a double entendre. It is when Jesus is confronted by a rich man, who asks "What is the path to heaven?" Jesus' reply in Greek has two meanings, which confuses the man. The trouble is Jesus would not have spoken Greek. He spoke Aramaic. And the word in Greek that is a double entendre is not a double entendre in Aramaic. I found that little gem fascinating.<br /><br />I could go on for hours on this topic. Having been indoctrinated in Christianity before I was old enough to comprehend what was happening to me, I found it engrossing to be presented with the reality of the bible rather than its myth.<br /><br />I believe in kindness, compassion and acceptance (better than tolerance), and I believe humanity and the world might be better served by the demise of religion.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8580530618613445245" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


